# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ohlc-charts
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] A **candlestick chart** (also called **Japanese candlestick chart** or **K-line**) is a style of financial chart used to describe price movements of a security, derivative, or currency.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] While similar in appearance to a bar chart, each "candle" represents four important pieces of information for that day: open and close in the thick body, and high and low in the "candle wick".
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Being densely packed with information, it tends to represent trading patterns over short periods of time, often a few days or a few trading sessions.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Candlestick charts are most often used in technical analysis of equity and currency price patterns.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] They are used by traders to determine possible price movement based on past patterns, and who use the opening price, closing price, high and low of that time period.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] They are visually similar to box plots, though box plots show different information.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Candlestick charts are thought to have been developed in the 18th century by Munehisa Homma, a Japanese rice trader.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] They were introduced to the Western world by Steve Nison in his book *Japanese Candlestick Charting Techniques*, first published in 1991.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] They are often used today in stock analysis along with other analytical tools such as Fibonacci analysis.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] The area between the open and the close is called the *real body*, price excursions above and below the real body are *shadows* (also called *wicks*).
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Wicks illustrate the highest and lowest traded prices of an asset during the time interval represented.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] The body illustrates the opening and closing trades.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] The price range is the distance between the top of the upper shadow and the bottom of the lower shadow moved through during the time frame of the candlestick.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] The range is calculated by subtracting the low price from the high price.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] The fill or the color of the candle's body represent the price change during the period.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Normally, if the asset closed higher than it opened, the body is displayed as hollow (or the green color is used), with the opening price at the bottom of the body and the closing price at the top.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Conversely, if the asset closed lower than it opened, the body is displayed as filled (or the red color is used), with the opening price at the top and the closing price at the bottom.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Modern charting software permits unrestricted customization of candle looks and colors, so the actual look of rising or falling price candles may vary.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] A candlestick need not have either a body or a wick.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Generally, the longer the body of the candle, the more intense the trading.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Candlesticks can also show the current price as they're forming, whether the price moved up or down over the time phrase and the price range of the asset covered in that time.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Rather than using the open, high, low, and close values for a given time interval, candlesticks can also be constructed using the open, high, low, and close of a specified volume range (for example, 1,000; 100,000; 1 million shares per candlestick).
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] In modern charting software, volume can be incorporated into candlestick charts by increasing or decreasing candlesticks width according to the relative volume for a given time period.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Candlestick charts are a visual aid for decision making in stock, foreign exchange, commodity, and option trading.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] By looking at a candlestick, one can identify an asset's opening and closing prices, highs and lows, and overall range for a specific time frame.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Candlestick charts serve as a cornerstone of technical analysis.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] For example, when the bar is white and high relative to other time periods, it means buyers are very bullish.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] The opposite is true when there is a black bar.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] A candlestick pattern is a particular sequence of candlesticks on a candlestick chart, which is mainly used to identify trends.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] The body of a Heikin-Ashi candle does not always represent the actual open/close.
[src:ohlc-charts/candlestick-chart] Unlike with regular candlesticks, a long wick shows more strength, whereas the same period on a standard chart might show a long body with little or no wick.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] A **fan chart** is made of a group of dispersion fan diagrams, which may be positioned according to two categorising dimensions.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] A *dispersion fan diagram* is a circular diagram which reports the same information about a dispersion as a box plot: namely median, quartiles, and two extreme values.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] 4. two *feathers* which indicate the extreme values.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The scale on the circular line begins at the left with the starting value (e. g. with zero).
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The following values are applicated clockwise.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The white tail of diameter indicates the median.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The dark fan indicates the dispersion of the middle half of the observed values; thus it encompasses the values from the first to the third quartile.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The white feathers indicate the dispersion of the middle 90% of the observed values.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The length of the white part of the diameter corresponds with the number of observations.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] A fan chart gives a quick summary of observed values which depend from two variables.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] This is possible thanks of a dense representation and a constant size which does not depend on the size of the single dispersion fan diagrams.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] An essential advantage compared to a sequence of box plots is the possibility to compare dispersion fan diagrams not only within one direction but within two directions (horizontally and vertically).
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The following example presents data from the data set *MathAchieve* which is part of the R package *nlme* of José Pinheiro et al.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] It contains mathematics achievement scores of 7185 students.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The students are categorised according to sex and membership of a minority ethnic group.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The graphics show the mathematics achievement scores in dependency on the socio-economic status of the students (x axis) and on the average socio-economic status of all students at the same school (y axis).
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The four graphic panels differentiate the students according to sex and membership of a minority ethnic group.
[src:ohlc-charts/fan-chart-statistics] The fan charts reveals clearly how the median value is partially following a big main tendency while the values of the single subgroups (with the cells) scatter largely what could lead to doubts about a possible correlation.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] The **Kagi chart** (Japanese: かぎ足, romanized: *kagiashi*) is a chart used for tracking price movements and to make decisions on purchasing stock.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] It differs from traditional stock charts such as the Candlestick chart by being mostly independent of time.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] This feature aids in producing a chart that reduces random noise.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] Due to its effectiveness in showing a clear path of price movements, the Kagi chart is one of the various charts that investors use to make better decisions about stocks.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] The most important benefit of this chart is that it is independent of time and change of direction occurs only when a specific amount is reached.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] Kagi chart signals are best used in conjunction with other forms of analysis.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] The Kagi chart was originally developed in Japan during the 1870s when the Japanese stock market started trading.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] It was used for tracking the price movement of rice and found use in determining the general levels of supply and demand for certain assets.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] Kagi charts look similar to swing charts and do not have a time axis.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] A Kagi chart is created with a series of vertical lines connected by short horizontal lines.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] Changes in line thickness are used to generate transaction signals.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] Buy signals are generated when the Kagi line goes from thin to thick and sell signals are generated when the line turns from thick to thin.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] Alternatively, thin and thick lines can be replaced with lines of different colours.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] Draw a thin vertical line from the starting price to each day's closing price, while the trend does not reverse.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] If a day's closing price moves in the opposite direction to the trend by more than the reversal amount, draw a short horizontal line and a new vertical line, beginning from the horizontal line to the new closing price.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] If the price on a day is greater than or equal to the previous high, change to a thick line and continue the vertical line.
[src:ohlc-charts/kagi-chart] If the price on that day is less than or equal to the previous low, then change to a thin line.
[src:ohlc-charts/open-high-low-close-chart] An **open-high-low-close chart** (**OHLC**) is a type of chart typically used in technical analysis to illustrate movements in the price of a financial instrument over time.
[src:ohlc-charts/open-high-low-close-chart] Each vertical line on the chart shows the price range (the highest and lowest prices) over one unit of time, e.g., one day or one hour.
[src:ohlc-charts/open-high-low-close-chart] Tick marks project from each side of the line indicating the opening price (e.g., for a daily bar chart this would be the starting price for that day) on the left, and the closing price for that time period on the right.
[src:ohlc-charts/open-high-low-close-chart] The bars may be shown in different hues depending on whether prices rose or fell in that period.
[src:ohlc-charts/open-high-low-close-chart] The Japanese candlestick chart and OHLC charts show exactly the same data, i.e., the opening, high, low, and closing prices during a particular time frame.
[src:ohlc-charts/open-high-low-close-chart] Day traders, who by default have to watch the price movements on a chart, prefer to use the Japanese candlesticks, because they show the "live action" price movements by expanding and contracting the candlestick's body, which is easier to grasp (and trade upon) than the standard OHLC bar.
[src:ohlc-charts/open-high-low-close-chart] Therefore, for dynamic real-time chart analysis, Japanese candlesticks offer advantages over standard OHLC bars.
[src:ohlc-charts/open-high-low-close-chart] In technical analysis OHLC charts are often combined with charts of other types such as line charts (showing moving average), column charts (trading volume), and range areas (Bollinger Bands).
[src:ohlc-charts/statistical-graphics] Whereas statistics and data analysis procedures generally yield their output in numeric or tabular form, graphical techniques allow such results to be displayed in some sort of pictorial form.
[src:ohlc-charts/statistical-graphics] They include plots such as scatter plots, histograms, probability plots, spaghetti plots, residual plots, box plots, block plots and biplots.
[src:ohlc-charts/statistical-graphics] Exploratory data analysis (EDA) relies heavily on such techniques.
[src:ohlc-charts/statistical-graphics] They can also provide insight into a data set to help with testing assumptions, model selection and regression model validation, estimator selection, relationship identification, factor effect determination, and outlier detection.
[src:ohlc-charts/statistical-graphics] In addition, the choice of appropriate statistical graphics can provide a convincing means of communicating the underlying message that is present in the data to others.
[src:ohlc-charts/statistical-graphics] If one is not using statistical graphics, then one is forfeiting insight into one or more aspects of the underlying structure of the data.
[src:ohlc-charts/statistical-graphics] Statistical graphics have been central to the development of science and date to the earliest attempts to analyse data.
[src:ohlc-charts/statistical-graphics] Many familiar forms, including bivariate plots, statistical maps, bar charts, and coordinate paper were used in the 18th century.
[src:ohlc-charts/statistical-graphics] Since the 1970s statistical graphics have been re-emerging as an important analytic tool with the revitalisation of computer graphics and related technologies.
[src:ohlc-charts/statistical-graphics] See the plots page for many more examples of statistical graphics.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] In mathematics, a **time series** is a sequence of data points indexed, listed, or graphed in chronological order.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Most commonly, a time series consists of observations recorded at successive equally spaced points in time.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Thus, it represents a form of discrete-time data.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A time series may describe measurements collected over seconds, days, years, or even centuries.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Common examples include heights of ocean tides, counts of sunspots, daily temperature readings, and the closing values of stock market indices such as the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A time series is often visualized using a run chart (a type of temporal line chart), which helps identify patterns such as trends, seasonal effects, and irregular fluctuations.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Time series data have a natural temporal ordering.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] This makes time series analysis distinct from cross-sectional studies, in which there is no natural ordering of the observations (e.g. explaining people's wages by reference to their respective education levels, where the individuals' data could be entered in any order).
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Time series analysis is also distinct from spatial data analysis where the observations typically relate to geographical locations (e.g. accounting for house prices by the location as well as the intrinsic characteristics of the houses).
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A stochastic model for a time series will generally reflect the fact that observations close together in time will be more closely related than observations further apart.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] In addition, time series models will often make use of the natural one-way ordering of time so that values for a given period will be expressed as deriving in some way from past values, rather than from future values (see time reversibility).
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Time series analysis can be applied to real-valued, continuous data, discrete numeric data, or discrete symbolic data (i.e. sequences of characters, such as letters and words in the English language).
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Methods for time series analysis may be divided into two classes: frequency-domain methods and time-domain methods.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] The former include spectral analysis and wavelet analysis; the latter include auto-correlation and cross-correlation analysis.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] In the time domain, correlation and analysis can be made in a filter-like manner using scaled correlation, thereby mitigating the need to operate in the frequency domain.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Additionally, time series analysis techniques may be divided into parametric and non-parametric methods.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] The parametric approaches assume that the underlying stationary stochastic process has a certain structure which can be described using a small number of parameters (for example, using an autoregressive or moving-average model).
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] In these approaches, the task is to estimate the parameters of the model that describes the stochastic process.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] By contrast, non-parametric approaches explicitly estimate the covariance or the spectrum of the process without assuming that the process has any particular structure.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Methods of time series analysis may also be divided into linear and non-linear, and univariate and multivariate.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A time series is one type of panel data.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Panel data is the general class, a multidimensional data set, whereas a time series data set is a one-dimensional panel (as is a cross-sectional dataset).
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A data set may exhibit characteristics of both panel data and time series data.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] One way to tell is to ask what makes one data record unique from the other records.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] If the answer is the time data field, then this is a time series data set candidate.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] If determining a unique record requires a time data field and an additional identifier which is unrelated to time (e.g. student ID, stock symbol, country code), then it is panel data candidate.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] If the differentiation lies on the non-time identifier, then the data set is a cross-sectional data set candidate.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] There are several types of motivation and data analysis available for time series which are appropriate for different purposes.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] In the context of statistics, econometrics, quantitative finance, seismology, meteorology, and geophysics the primary goal of time series analysis is forecasting.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] In the context of signal processing, control engineering and communication engineering it is used for signal detection.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Other applications are in data mining, pattern recognition and machine learning, where time series analysis can be used for clustering, classification, query by content, anomaly detection as well as forecasting.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A simple way to examine a regular time series is manually with a line chart.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] The datagraphic shows tuberculosis deaths in the United States, along with the yearly change and the percentage change from year to year.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] The total number of deaths declined in every year until the mid-1980s, after which there were occasional increases, often proportionately - but not absolutely - quite large.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A study of corporate data analysts found two challenges to exploratory time series analysis: discovering the shape of interesting patterns, and finding an explanation for these patterns.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Visual tools that represent time series data as heat map matrices can help overcome these challenges.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] This approach may be based on harmonic analysis and filtering of signals in the frequency domain using the Fourier transform, and spectral density estimation.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Its development was significantly accelerated during World War II by mathematician Norbert Wiener, electrical engineers Rudolf E.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Kálmán, Dennis Gabor and others for filtering signals from noise and predicting signal values at a certain point in time.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] An equivalent effect may be achieved in the time domain, as in a Kalman filter; see filtering and smoothing for more techniques.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Curve fitting is the process of constructing a curve, or mathematical function, that has the best fit to a series of data points, possibly subject to constraints.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Curve fitting can involve either interpolation, where an exact fit to the data is required, or smoothing, in which a "smooth" function is constructed that approximately fits the data.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A related topic is regression analysis, which focuses more on questions of statistical inference such as how much uncertainty is present in a curve that is fit to data observed with random errors.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Fitted curves can be used as an aid for data visualization, to infer values of a function where no data are available, and to summarize the relationships among two or more variables.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Extrapolation refers to the use of a fitted curve beyond the range of the observed data, and is subject to a degree of uncertainty since it may reflect the method used to construct the curve as much as it reflects the observed data.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] For processes that are expected to generally grow in magnitude one of the curves in the graphic (and many others) can be fitted by estimating their parameters.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] The construction of economic time series involves the estimation of some components for some dates by interpolation between values ("benchmarks") for earlier and later dates.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Interpolation is estimation of an unknown quantity between two known quantities (historical data), or drawing conclusions about missing information from the available information ("reading between the lines").
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Interpolation is useful where the data surrounding the missing data is available and its trend, seasonality, and longer-term cycles are known.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] This is often done by using a related series known for all relevant dates.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Alternatively polynomial interpolation or spline interpolation is used where piecewise polynomial functions are fitted in time intervals such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A different problem which is closely related to interpolation is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function (also called regression).
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] The main difference between regression and interpolation is that polynomial regression gives a single polynomial that models the entire data set.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Spline interpolation, however, yield a piecewise continuous function composed of many polynomials to model the data set.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Extrapolation is the process of estimating, beyond the original observation range, the value of a variable on the basis of its relationship with another variable.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] It is similar to interpolation, which produces estimates between known observations, but extrapolation is subject to greater uncertainty and a higher risk of producing meaningless results.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] In general, a function approximation problem asks us to select a function among a well-defined class that closely matches ("approximates") a target function in a task-specific way.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Second, the target function, call it *g*, may be unknown; instead of an explicit formula, only a set of points (a time series) of the form (*x*, *g*(*x*)) is provided.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Depending on the structure of the domain and codomain of *g*, several techniques for approximating *g* may be applicable.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] For example, if *g* is an operation on the real numbers, techniques of interpolation, extrapolation, regression analysis, and curve fitting can be used.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] If the codomain (range or target set) of *g* is a finite set, one is dealing with a classification problem instead.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A related problem of *online* time series approximation is to summarize the data in one-pass and construct an approximate representation that can support a variety of time series queries with bounds on worst-case error.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] To some extent, the different problems (regression, classification, fitness approximation) have received a unified treatment in statistical learning theory, where they are viewed as supervised learning problems.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] In statistics, prediction is a part of statistical inference.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] One particular approach to such inference is known as predictive inference, but the prediction can be undertaken within any of the several approaches to statistical inference.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Indeed, one description of statistics is that it provides a means of transferring knowledge about a sample of a population to the whole population, and to other related populations, which is not necessarily the same as prediction over time.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] When information is transferred across time, often to specific points in time, the process is known as forecasting.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Assigning time series pattern to a specific category, for example identify a word based on series of hand movements in sign language.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Splitting a time-series into a sequence of segments.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] It is often the case that a time-series can be represented as a sequence of individual segments, each with its own characteristic properties.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] For example, the audio signal from a conference call can be partitioned into pieces corresponding to the times during which each person was speaking.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] In time-series segmentation, the goal is to identify the segment boundary points in the time-series, and to characterize the dynamical properties associated with each segment.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] One can approach this problem using change-point detection, or by modeling the time-series as a more sophisticated system, such as a Markov jump linear system.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Time series data may be clustered, however special care has to be taken when considering subsequence clustering.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Subsequence time series clustering resulted in unstable (random) clusters *induced by the feature extraction* using chunking with sliding windows.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] It was found that the cluster centers (the average of the time series in a cluster - also a time series) follow an arbitrarily shifted sine pattern (regardless of the dataset, even on realizations of a random walk).
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] This means that the found cluster centers are non-descriptive for the dataset because the cluster centers are always nonrepresentative sine waves.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Models for time series data can have many forms and represent different stochastic processes.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] When modeling variations in the level of a process, three broad classes of practical importance are the *autoregressive* (AR) models, the *integrated* (I) models, and the *moving-average* (MA) models.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] These three classes depend *linearly* on previous data points.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Combinations of these ideas produce autoregressive moving-average (ARMA) and autoregressive integrated moving-average (ARIMA) models.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] The autoregressive fractionally integrated moving-average (ARFIMA) model generalizes the former three.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Another important generalization is the time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) model, in which the AR coefficients are allowed to change over time, enabling the model to capture evolving or non-stationary dynamics.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Extensions of these classes to deal with vector-valued data are available under the heading of multivariate time-series models and sometimes the preceding acronyms are extended by including an initial "V" for "vector", as in VAR for vector autoregression.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] For these models, the acronyms are extended with a final "X" for "exogenous".
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Time-varying autoregressive (TVAR) models are especially useful for analyzing non-stationary time series in which the underlying dynamics evolve over time in complex ways, not limited to classical forms of variation such as trends or seasonal patterns.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] This flexibility makes them well suited to modeling structural changes, regime shifts, or gradual evolutions in a system's behavior.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Estimation of TVAR models typically involves methods such as kernel smoothing, recursive least squares, or Kalman filtering.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Non-linear dependence of the level of a series on previous data points is of interest, partly because of the possibility of producing a chaotic time series.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] However, more importantly, empirical investigations can indicate the advantage of using predictions derived from non-linear models, over those from linear models, as for example in nonlinear autoregressive exogenous models.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Among other types of non-linear time series models, there are models to represent the changes of variance over time (heteroskedasticity).
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] These models represent autoregressive conditional heteroskedasticity (ARCH) and the collection comprises a wide variety of representation (GARCH, TARCH, EGARCH, FIGARCH, CGARCH, etc.).
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Here changes in variability are related to, or predicted by, recent past values of the observed series.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] This is in contrast to other possible representations of locally varying variability, where the variability might be modeled as being driven by a separate time-varying process, as in a doubly stochastic model.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Multiscale (often referred to as multiresolution) techniques decompose a given time series, attempting to illustrate time dependence at multiple scales.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] See also Markov switching multifractal (MSMF) techniques for modeling volatility evolution.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A hidden Markov model (HMM) is a statistical Markov model in which the system being modeled is assumed to be a Markov process with unobserved (hidden) states.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] An HMM can be considered as the simplest dynamic Bayesian network.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] HMM models are widely used in speech recognition, for translating a time series of spoken words into text.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Many of these models are collected in the python package sktime.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] A number of different notations are in use for time-series analysis.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Ergodicity implies stationarity, but the converse is not necessarily the case.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Stationarity is usually classified into strict stationarity and wide-sense or second-order stationarity.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Both models and applications can be developed under each of these conditions, although the models in the latter case might be considered as only partly specified.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] In addition, time-series analysis can be applied where the series are seasonally stationary or non-stationary.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Situations where the amplitudes of frequency components change with time can be dealt with in time-frequency analysis which makes use of a time–frequency representation of a time-series or signal.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Time series can be visualized with two categories of chart: Overlapping Charts and Separated Charts.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] Jevons was the first to study times series.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] In his book he examined a number of weekly financial time series between the years 1825 to 1860 inclusive.
[src:ohlc-charts/time-series] These included times series of bankruptcies, currency circulation and discount rates.
